
# |<----   Preferably using up to 50 chars   --->|<--- max 72 chars -->|

# ** Example template:
# [type]: [subject]
#
# [optional body]
#
# [optional footer]

# A properly formed Git commit subject line should always be able to
# complete the following sentence:
#     * If applied, this commit <will your subject line here>

# ** Type
# Must be one of the following:
# * feat:       A new feature for the user, not a new feature for a build script
# * fix:        Bug fix for the user, not a fix to a build scripts
# * refactor:   Refactoring production code
# * chore:      No production code change
# * docs:       Changes to documentation
# * style:      Formatting, missing semicolons, etc.; no code change
# * perf:       Code improved in terms of processing performance
# * vendor:     Update version for dependencies, packages
# * test:       Adding missing tests, refactoring tests; no production code change
# * ci:         Changes to CI configuration files and scripts

# ** Rules
# The 7 rules of a great commit message
#    1. Separate subject from body with a blank line
#    2. Limit the subject line to 50 characters
#    3. Do no capitalize the subject line
#    4. Do not end the subject line with a period
#    5. Use the imperative mood in the subject line
#    6. Wrap the body at preferably 50 characters, max 72 characters
#    7. Use the body to explain what and why opposed to how

